<DOC><DOCNO> AP880521-0068 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0653EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Poll     05-21 0229</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Poll,0235</SECOND><HEAD>Most Soviets Believe Relations With U.S. Satisfactory, Pravda Says</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Most Soviet citizens surveyed in a public opinionpoll believe relations with the United States are satisfactory butunstable, Pravda reported today.   The Communist Party daily said 67 percent of those surveyeddescribed relations as satisfactory, 8 percent said they were goodand 6 percent characterized relations as bad.   Pravda said in an article headlined ``The Barometer of Hopes''that it wanted to report Soviets' views of U.S.-Soviet relationsbecause it had published a similar poll of Americans on May 12.   President Reagan arrives in Moscow on May 29 for his fourthsummit with Mikhail S. Gorbachev.   Pravda said two-thirds of those questioned characterized changesin Soviet-American relations after the three previous summits as``significant but unstable.''   Pravda said the poll was conducted by a group in the Institutefor Sociological Research of the Soviet Academy of Sciences alongwith the Center for Study of Public Opinion of the Communist Partyin the Georgian republic.   Pravda said 1,200 people were interviewed in 12 regions of theRussian republic and several regions of Georgia. It did not saywhen or how the poll was conducted or give a margin of error.   The poll of Americans published by Pravda on May 12 said 61percent of those surveyed believed relations between the twocountries are improving.</TEXT></DOC>